text: Last week, Biden approved a military transfer of $80 million for Taiwan under the Foreign Military Financing (FMF), a program typically used for sovereign states. In response, China’s state-run newspaper has stated that the U.S. has crossed a red line with “lethal consequences.” We are badly screwing up our posture & it doesn’t have to be this way. Right now the U.S. embraces the “One China” Policy, which fails to recognize Taiwan as a nation & adopts “strategic ambiguity” about whether or not the U.S. will defend Taiwan against invasion. This creates mutual confusion with China about red lines & increases the risk of major conflict between the U.S. and China, especially heightened in the near-term when the entire U.S. economy and modern way of life relies on leading-edge semiconductors manufactured in Taiwan. It is a vital U.S. national security interest to ensure that China *does not* acquire sole control of the global semiconductor supply chain, so the U.S. should shift from strategic ambiguity to strategic clarity: commit to affirmatively *defend Taiwan against Chinese annexation until the U.S. achieves semiconductor independence*, at which point the U.S. should resume its current posture of strategic ambiguity. In the meantime, Taiwan can double its own military expenditures to a more rational 4-5% of GDP while the U.S. bolsters its own military and economic alliances with India, Japan, and South Korea and fortifies our own homeland defense capabilities – including but not limited to nuclear missile, super-EMP, and cyber defenses. This is how we can stop Chinese aggression and advance vital long-run U.S. interests while avoiding World War III. I am the only U.S. Presidential candidate in either political party who has offered a clear vision for how to achieve this goal.

text: Happy #LaborDay everyone! FACT: Union members make 18% more on average than non-union members and are 60% more likely to have health benefits and almost twice as likely to have retirement benefits. Unions provide many benefits to workers, including: - Collective Bargaining: Unions can negotiate with employers on behalf of their members to secure better wages, benefits, and working conditions. By joining together, workers have a greater bargaining power than they would individually. - Improved Job Security: Unions can help protect workers from layoffs or unjust termination by negotiating job security provisions in collective bargaining agreements. - Improved Compensation: Unions can negotiate for higher wages, overtime pay, and benefits like health insurance, retirement plans, and paid time off. - Workplace Safety: Unions can help improve workplace safety by negotiating for better safety equipment, training, and procedures. - Training and Professional Development: Unions can help their members access training and professional development opportunities to improve their skills and advance their careers. - Advocacy: Unions can advocate for workers' rights and represent them in disputes with employers, including grievances and legal actions. - Political Power: Unions can use their collective power to influence public policy and elect politicians who support workers' rights. Overall, unions can help workers achieve greater economic security, better working conditions, and a stronger voice in the workplace and the broader society. #SolidaritySummer

text: Happy Labor Day Everyone! I walked the picket line again this weekend with hotel housekeepers striking against inhumane treatment, including anti-strike violence by Fairmont Miramar Hotel in Los Angeles. Fairmont housekeepers clean 14 to 15 large rooms a day. The hotel, which cut staff during COVID, is now enjoying pre-COVID occupancy rates and profits but nevertheless wants to increase daily workloads to 18 rooms to compensate for understaffing. 3 out of every 5 workers is injured on the job each year due to repetitive lifting of heavy mattresses + bending to scrub and clean. Workers typically commute 2 hours from Palmdale or Victorville because of the unaffordable housing in Santa Monica. Some live in their cars during the work week to save gas money. Many of the workers also work two jobs to keep up with inflation. As he laid off hundreds of hotel workers during the pandemic, Hilton’s CEO doubled his own salary from $10 million to $20 million annually.
